            "answer_text": "It depends on how you define smart. Many Founding Fathers were sharp, clever, and/or intelligent. Some were educated; others were not. Of those who received schooling, Charles Carroll of Carrollton may have been the most formally educated; he surely was the most educated of all the Declaration of Independence Signers. Carroll, who was Catholic, began his education at a Jesuit school on Maryland\u2019s Eastern Shore; however, during this time, a law was passed prohibiting a Catholic education in Maryland. In response to this new law, Carroll's wealthy family sent young Charley abroad at age 11 to be educated in Belgium, France, and England, where he studied law before returning to Maryland at age 27. When he returned home to Maryland, Charley was fluent in five languages. Carroll received land from his father upon his return from Europe, and by making shrewd, sound financial decisions, Carroll grew his family fortune further\u2014investing in such entities as the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad, the Chesapeake and Ohio Canal, roads, banks, and so on. Carroll was \u201cbook smart\u201d but also possessed an analytical and reasonable mind. On the other hand, Benjamin Franklin, with little formal education, was perhaps the most brilliant Founding Father. This gifted genius was a printer, author, inventor, scientist, philosopher, diplomat, postmaster, and more. Franklin, during his lifetime, was well known on both sides of the Atlantic. Franklin was a thinker and a doer. He created things as he saw a need for them. He experimented and took risks. My opinion is such that if Benjamin Franklin were alive in the modern world today, of course, he would be internationally famous (because he would have invented the internet), but he also would own thousands of patents, would be a Nobel Prize winner (among his other prestigious awards), and would have his own YouTube channel with millions of followers waiting to see what he would do or say next. Franklin was a creator; he was smart in a clever and witty way. ",
